f the Theosophical Society in very different regional contexts, ranging from India, Vietnam, China, and Japan to Victorian Britain and Israel, shedding new light on the entanglement of "Western" and "Oriental" ideas around 1900. The second half explores specific cultural influences that Theosophy exerted in the spheres of literature, art, and politics, using case studies from Sri Lanka, Burma, India, Japan, Ireland, Germany, and Russia. The examples clearly show that Theosophy was part of a truly global movement, thus providing an outstanding example of the complex entanglements of the global religious history of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aPhilosophy : New Age. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Esotericism and Gnosticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theosophy. 7aRELIGION / Theosophy.2bisacsh1 aBergunder, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChienhui, Chuang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanegraaff, Wouter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarlass, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuss, Boaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJammes, Jérémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrämer, Hans Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrämer, Hans Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMyers, Perry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeidel-Dreffke, Björn, econtributor.4ctb4https: